message.raw:
This code reliably timesout quickly and throws an exception, halting the worker,
if no trigger pulse arrives. However, if there has been an abort, the abort is successful
but on a subsequent run with a trigger fail something goes wrong with the syncronisation
acquisition_done and a trigger-fail leads to it continuing to write the data to the HDF5 file.

message.raw:
* Enable TRIGSYNC so that both channels receive hardware trigger on pin3 of DB15
* Attempt ot enable synchronous table mode i.e. TABLE,SYNC (intermittently works)
* Disabled automatic TABLE,RESTART owing to non-deterministic results in testing
* Ditto for TABLE,REARM on CH1 (whereas TABLE,REARM must be enabled on ch2)
* Removed unused generic communication methods (ask_dict, set_get, stt_timeout)
* Removed specific comms methods (parse_response, get_val, set_val, program_static)
* In program_manual, only call STOP/START on ch1
* Made smart-programming equality check more concise
* In parse_entry (used by check_remote_values), removed magic number in place of
  freq_conv.MHz_to_base.
* Populatd shutdown method of Worker with self.close()

message.raw:
* Added get_default_unit_conversion_classes (as per NovatechDDS9m) to use
  MOGLabsDDS amplitude and frequency conversion classes by default. This removes
  the requirement to specify unit conversion classes at every instantiation.
* Changed base_units of the DeviceTab from MHz to Hz. Amplitude base remains int
* Implemented smart programming (checks gate and duration of each instruction).
* During __init__ of Worker:
    - turn TRIGSYNC on
    - ensure table is only 2 instructions long.
    - turn SYNC off (this will be changed soon, but is broken currently).
    - enable automatic TABLE,RESTART. This is buggy before a table is programmed.
* Use unit conversion classes when:
    - Returning amplitude from check_remote_values (device returns non-native unit).
    - Parsing front panel values and table instructions (base_unit of freq is not native to device).
* Fixed bug where table_length was not cast to integer when checking smart_cache

to our testing) phase coherent output when using a simple delay line for
synchronous output rather than a tri-state driver as Monash is using.

message.raw:
Added workaround for old pulseblasters which do not report their status
and as such have no way to detect end-of-run. End-of-run is now based
on a fixed duration equal to the shot duration plus some extra time
to account for waits and software delays.

This change is backward compatible.
